# v0.5.0 тАФ 2026-06-12 тАФ benoitcayladbx

## Fix: Deleted class attributes reappear in OWL export (issue #50)

**Context**: Reported in
[databrickslabs/ontobricks#50](https://github.com/databrickslabs/ontobricks/issues/50).
When an `owl:DatatypeProperty` (a class attribute) was deleted in the ontology
designer, the deleted property reappeared as a `DatatypeProperty` in every
subsequent OWL/Turtle export.

**Root cause**: Domain-scoped datatype properties are stored in two places once
an OWL file is parsed тАФ `classes[].dataProperties` (the authoritative attribute
list the designer mutates) and a shadow entry in the top-level `properties[]`
list (`OntologyParser.get_properties()` legitimately returns every property,
including datatype ones, and `apply_parsed_owl_to_domain` persists both). When
an attribute is deleted in the designer only `classes[].dataProperties` is
updated; the shadow in `properties[]` survives. `OntologyGenerator.generate()`
emits class attributes from *both* paths тАФ `_add_class()` тЖТ
`_add_data_property_for_class()` *and* `_add_property()` for the `properties[]`
list тАФ so `_add_property()` re-emitted the stale shadow and the deleted
attribute came back on export.

Changing `get_properties()` to drop datatype properties was rejected: its
contract (and downstream consumers / tests) rely on it returning all
properties. The fix is therefore applied at the single export choke point, the
generator, which treats `classes[].dataProperties` as the source of truth for
class attributes.

**Changes**:
1. `src/back/core/w3c/owl/OntologyGenerator.py` тАФ added `_local_name()`,
   `_build_class_attr_index()` (built once in `__init__`, maps each class тАФ by
   name and by URI local name тАФ to the set of attribute local names it
   declares) and `_is_stale_datatype_shadow()`. In `_add_property()`, a
   `DatatypeProperty` whose domain class is known but no longer declares that
   attribute is now skipped (logged at debug). The check is conservative: an
   empty domain or an unknown domain class is never dropped, so object
   properties, domain-less datatype properties and surviving attributes
   (including their declared range, e.g. `xsd:integer`) are unaffected.
2. `tests/units/ontology/test_owl_generator.py` тАФ added
   `TestDeletedAttributeNotReexported` with four regression tests: stale shadow
   skipped, surviving shadow (and its range) kept, unknown-domain datatype
   property kept, and a full parse тЖТ delete-attribute тЖТ regenerate round-trip.

**Modified files**:
- `src/back/core/w3c/owl/OntologyGenerator.py`
- `tests/units/ontology/test_owl_generator.py`

**Test result**: `python -m pytest tests/units --ignore=tests/property` тЖТ
**2277 passed, 15 skipped**. The two new reproduction tests fail before the fix
and pass after it; the two conservative-behaviour tests pass throughout.
(`tests/property/test_owl_roundtrip.py` is skipped тАФ the `hypothesis` package is
not installed in this environment, unrelated to this change.)

## Fix: Expanded nodes grouped under identifier instead of entity type (issue #52)

**Context**: Reported in
[databrickslabs/ontobricks#52](https://github.com/databrickslabs/ontobricks/issues/52).
Using the knowledge graph viewer's right-click тЖТ "Expand neighbours" action,
newly added nodes appeared in the View pane as brand-new entity types named
after their identifiers (and with random colours) instead of being grouped
under their existing entity type. This broke entity-type filtering and the
type-based colour coding.

**Root cause**: The `/dtwin/neighbors` endpoint
(`src/api/routers/internal/dtwin.py`) returns the induced subgraph of the
visited instance URIs. To avoid "ghost endpoints", it dropped any triple whose
object is a URI not present in the visited set. The `rdf:type` triple's object
is the *class* URI (e.g. `тАж/Person`), which is an ontology class тАФ never an
instance, so never in the visited set. Those type triples were therefore
filtered out, and the front-end (`buildGraph` in `query-d3graph.js`) received
untyped nodes. With no `rdf:type`, it falls back to `inferTypeFromUri()`, which
derives a pseudo-type from the URI's local part тАФ i.e. the node's identifier тАФ
producing the new ad-hoc groups and random colours.

**Changes**:
1. `src/api/routers/internal/dtwin.py` тАФ extracted the inline neighbour-triple
   filtering into a testable module-level helper `_filter_neighbor_triples()`
   plus `_is_type_predicate()` / `_RDF_TYPE_URI`. The filter now keeps a triple
   when its object is a literal, when its object URI is in the visited set, **or
   when it is an `rdf:type` triple** (full URI or a `#type`/`/type` suffix),
   mirroring the predicate detection used by the front-end. Class URIs in type
   triples don't create ghost nodes because `buildGraph`'s pre-pass already
   recognises them as type URIs and excludes them from entities.
2. `tests/units/api/test_routes.py` тАФ added `TestNeighborTripleFilter` with six
   regression tests: rdf:type kept when class URI not visited (the #52 case),
   short `#type` predicate kept, non-type URI object outside visited dropped,
   URI object within visited kept, literal object kept, and de-dup + limit
   handling.

**Modified files**:
- `src/api/routers/internal/dtwin.py`
- `tests/units/api/test_routes.py`

**Test result**: `python -m pytest tests/units` тЖТ **2328 passed, 11 skipped**.
(`tests/property/*` still skipped due to the missing `hypothesis` package,
unrelated to this change.)
